    "value": "**EN 18031** is a European standard series developed specifically to help manufacturers comply with the new cybersecurity requirements implemented under the EU’s Radio Equipment Directive (RED) 2014/53/EU, as updated by Delegated Regulation (EU) 2022/30. As of August 1, 2025, compliance with these cybersecurity requirements is mandatory for any radio equipment placed on the EU market. Here is an authoritative summary of EN 18031 and its use:\n\n### What is EN 18031?\n\n- **EN 18031** is a harmonized set of European standards designed to directly address the mandatory cybersecurity provisions set out by the RED’s Articles 3.3 (d), (e), and (f), which require:\n  - Protection against network harm (network integrity and proper use of resources)\n  - Safeguards for personal data and user privacy\n  - Measures to prevent fraud in devices handling monetary value or virtual currency【3:0†source】【3:2†source】【3:3†source】【3:5†source】【3:8†source】\n\n- The standards were developed by CEN and CENELEC’s Joint Technical Committee for Cybersecurity and Data Protection, reflecting state-of-the-art best practices and regulatory requirements.\n\n### Structure of EN 18031\n\nThe standard is divided into three parts, each aligned with one of the key cybersecurity risk categories in the RED:\n1. **EN 18031-1:** Requirements for all internet-connected radio equipment. Focuses on securing devices to prevent harm to networks, unauthorized access, and general cybersecurity threats.\n2. **EN 18031-2:** Applies to radio equipment processing personal, traffic, or location data (e.g., wearable devices, smart toys, childcare gadgets). Centers on technical and organizational measures to protect user data and privacy.\n3. **EN 18031-3:** Covers equipment capable of processing virtual currency or monetary value (e.g., payment terminals). Ensures controls against financial fraud, transaction integrity, and secure handling of sensitive transactions【3:0†source】【3:2†source】【3:3†source】【3:5†source】【3:8†source】.\n\n### Application and Compliance Process\n\n- **Presumption of conformity**: By fully implementing EN 18031, manufacturers can claim \"presumption of conformity\"—effectively a fast route to CE marking—showing that their product meets the RED’s cybersecurity requirements. Products that do not align fully, or that use alternate solutions, must engage a Notified Body for external assessment【3:5†source】【3:6†source】.\n- **Scope**: EN 18031 requirements are broad, covering consumer IoT, smart home devices, wearables, smart toys, payment terminals, and any radio-equipped product with connectivity features—notable exclusions include devices already covered by certain sector-specific EU regulations (e.g., medical and automotive)【3:1†source】.\n- **Requirements**: The standards entail concrete technical requirements including secure authentication, encrypted communications, network/resource protection, secure update mechanisms, user access control, and privacy-by-design principles. EN 18031 also recommends structured threat analysis using frameworks such as STRIDE【3:7†source】.\n\n### How It Is Used for RED Cybersecurity\n\n- **Mandatory baseline**: From August 1, 2025, radio equipment must comply with these standards to be legally placed on the EU market.\n- **Assessment paths**: Compliance can be demonstrated through self-assessment (if following the standard to the letter), or via Notified Body assessment when deviating from the standard or triggering restricted clauses (e.g., omitting mandatory password requirements).\n- **Ongoing obligations**: Compliance is not a one-time event—manufacturers must maintain documentation, update processes, and respond to emerging threats in line with EN 18031 over the product lifecycle【3:8†source】【3:9†source】.\n\n### Authoritative Summary\n\nEN 18031 provides the essential framework for cybersecurity compliance under the RED, setting the new baseline for market access of radio equipment in the EU. It focuses on ensuring robust network security, user privacy, and fraud prevention in all relevant radio-enabled products. Its harmonized status means that manufacturers following EN 18031 are presumed to meet the legal requirements, simplifying CE marking and facilitating smooth EU market entry. Compliance with EN 18031 will be enforced via market surveillance and product recalls for noncompliant devices【3:2†source】【3:5†source】【3:6†source】【3:8†source】【3:9†source】. \n\n**In summary**, EN 18031 is now the principal European cybersecurity standard for radio equipment, and alignment with it is the surest path to meeting the RED's new legal cybersecurity demands.",
